In [ ]:
mse = function(x, y) mean((x-y)^2)

bias = function(x, y) mean(x-y)

estimate = function(estimator, θ, sd, distribution = rnorm, n = 50, times = 10000) {
	estimations = numeric(times)
	for (i in 1:times) {
		sample = distribution(n, θ, sd)
		estimations[i] = estimator(sample)
	}

	return (c(
		mean 		= mean(estimations),
		MSE 		= mse(θ, estimations),
		bias 		= bias(θ, estimations),
		variance	= var(estimations)
	))
}
In [ ]:
quickplot = function(f, from = -4, to = 4) {
	x = seq(from, to, length=100)
	plot(x, f(x), type = "l", ylab="", xlab="", axes = FALSE)
	axis(1, at = from:to)
}

Specific weighted sum¶

In [ ]:
w = function(i, n) {
	f = function(x) dnorm(qnorm(x/n))
	f(i - 1) - f(i)
}

wi_weight_sum = function(sample) {
	n = length(sample)
	sum(sort(sample) * mapply(w, 1:n, n))
}

quickplot(function (x) mapply(w, x, length(x)), from=1, to=100)

It is noticeable that the quality of estimates depends heavily upon the scale parameter while the change in shift parameters appears to have no impact on the error metrics whatsoever. All results are decent except for the last experiment where there is an apparent problem. We see that in the cases $b$ and $c$ we deviate a lot from the true parameter value, reflected in spikes of MSE and bias. Interestingly, this estimator seems to perform well on scale parameter instead:

When conducting experiments involving random processes (e.g., sampling, bootstrapping), setting the seed ensures that the results can be replicated.

In [ ]:
set.seed(1)
a = rnorm(100)

set.seed(1)
b = rnorm(100)

identical(a, b)
TRUE

Setting the seed helps track and verify the behavior and validity of the code under consistent conditions. It is also useful for model and method comparisons on randomized data.

Exercise 3¶

In order to find the Maximum Likelihood Estimator for the shift parameter in the logistic distribution, one typically needs to solve the first derivative equation that maximizes the likelihood function. This process may necessitate the use of numerical methods since the likelihood function often contains nonlinear terms, which can make analytical solutions for the first derivative equation difficult or even impossible to obtain. In the case of logistic distribution we do not have a closed form solution for the first derivative equation:

$$\frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \theta} = \frac{n}{s} - \frac{2}{s}\sum_{i}^{n} \frac{e^\frac{\theta - x_i}{s}}{1+e^\frac{\theta - x_i}{s}} = 0$$

Exercise 4 (Regula Falsi)¶

Description¶

The Regula Falsi method is a numerical method for finding the roots of a mathematical equation. It's an iterative algorithm that repeatedly narrows down the range in which the root is believed to be located.

Assumptions¶

  1. Exactly one root exists in the specified search interval [a, b]
  2. $f(a) \cdot f(b) < 0$
  3. $f',f''$ have constant sign on [a, b]

Algorithm¶

  1. Choose an initial interval $[a, b]$ such that $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs, i.e., $f(a) \times f(b) < 0$.

  2. Compute the next approximation $c$ using the formula:

    $c = \frac{{a \cdot f(b) - b \cdot f(a)}}{{f(b) - f(a)}}$

  3. Evaluate $f(c)$.

  4. Update the interval:

    • If $f(c)$ is close enough to zero (i.e., $|f(c)|$ is less than a predefined tolerance), then $c$ is considered a good approximation of the root, and the algorithm terminates.
    • Otherwise, update the interval:
      • If $f(c)$ has the same sign as $f(a)$, set $a = c$.
      • If $f(c)$ has the same sign as $f(b)$, set $b = c$.

  5. Repeat steps 2 to 4 until the approximation $c$ is within the desired tolerance.

In [ ]:
RF = function(f, a, b, error = 0.0001, max_iters = 10000) {
	iters = 0; c = a
	while ((iters = iters + 1) < max_iters) {
		fa = f(a); fb = f(b)

		c = (a*fb - b*fa) / (fb - fa)
		fc = f(c)

		if (fa * fc < 0)
			b = c
		else
			a = c

		if (abs(fc) <= error) return(c)
		if (abs(a - b) <= error) return(c)
	}
	warning("Maximum iterations reached. Solution may not be accurate.")
	return (c)
}
In [ ]:
# sanity check
RF(function(x) x^2 - 4, 1, 3)
1.99998293340615

Exercise 5¶

In [ ]:
quickplot(dlogis)

The probability density function (PDF) of the logistic distribution is given by:

$$f(x | \theta, s) = \frac{1}{s \pi} \cdot \frac{e^{-(x - \theta)/s}}{(1 + e^{-(x - \theta)/s})^2}$$

To find the MLE of the logistic distribution is to find the value of $\theta$ that maximizes the likelihood function. The likelihood function, denoted as $L(\theta, x)$, is the product of the PDF for each data point:

$$L(\theta) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} f(x_i | \theta, s)$$

To maximize this likelihood function, it's often more convenient to work with the log-likelihood function as it simplifies the calculations:

$$\ell(\theta, s) = log L(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{\theta - x_i}{s} - 2\sum_{i=1}^{n} log(1 + e^\frac{\theta - x_i}{s}) $$

We can use calculus optimization methods and look for a $\theta$ for which the first derivative is zero.

$$\frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \theta} = \frac{n}{s} - \frac{2}{s}\sum_{i}^{n} \frac{e^\frac{\theta - x_i}{s}}{1+e^\frac{\theta - x_i}{s}} = 0$$

Since we do not have a closed form of this equation we resolve to the use of numerical root finding methods instead.

In [ ]:
logistic_estimator = function(s) {
	return (function(sample) {
		a = min(sample)
		b = max(sample)
		n = length(sample)

		f = function(θ) {
			e = exp((θ - sample) / s)
			return( (n - 2*sum(e / (1 + e))) / s)
		}

		return (RF(f, a, b))
	})
}
In [ ]:
a = estimate(estimator = logistic_estimator(1), distribution = rlogis, θ = 1, sd = 1)
b = estimate(estimator = logistic_estimator(1), distribution = rlogis, θ = 4, sd = 1)
c = estimate(estimator = logistic_estimator(2), distribution = rlogis, θ = 1, sd = 2)
print(data.frame(a, b, c))

                   a             b           c
mean     0.998160721  4.0006135244 0.992168768
MSE      0.059683975  0.0598670213 0.241213500
bias     0.001839279 -0.0006135244 0.007831232
variance 0.059686561  0.0598726321 0.241176290

As we can see the obtained results match up nicely with the true paremeter value. Since we are using Regula Falsi we do not have to guess the real value of the parameter in question (like we would in, for example, a Newton's method), but if we did the sample mean would be a reasonable choice since logistic distribution is somewhat similar in shape to that of the normal distribution.

Excercise 6¶

In [ ]:
quickplot(dcauchy)

The probability density function (PDF) of the Cauchy distribution is given by:

$$ f(x | \theta, s) = \frac{1}{s\pi \left[1 + \left(\frac{x - \theta}{s}\right)^2\right]} $$

Then the log-likelihood is: $$\ell(\theta)=-nlog(s\pi) - \sum_{i=1}^{n} log(1+\frac{(x_i - \theta)^2}{s^2})$$

To find the MLE for $\theta$, set the derivative equal to zero and solve for $\theta$: $$\frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \theta} = 2\sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{x_i-\theta}{s^2 + (x_i-\theta)^2} = 0$$

In [ ]:
cauchy_estimator = function(s) {
	return (function(sample) {
		# it is not obvious what the reasonable range should be, but a range
		# too wide will not fascilitate convergence to a sensible result
		a = -10 #min(sample)
		b =  10 #max(sample)
		n = length(sample)

		f = function(θ) {
			diff = sample - θ
			return( sum(diff / (s^2 + diff^2)) )
		}
		return (RF(f, a, b))
	})
}
In [ ]:
a = estimate(estimator = cauchy_estimator(1), θ = 1, sd = 1, distribution = rcauchy)
b = estimate(estimator = cauchy_estimator(4), θ = 4, sd = 1, distribution = rcauchy)
c = estimate(estimator = cauchy_estimator(1), θ = 1, sd = 2, distribution = rcauchy)
print(data.frame(a, b, c))

                    a            b           c
mean      1.001206776 3.9998584916 0.997698585
MSE       0.043073588 0.0634735211 0.192698695
bias     -0.001206776 0.0001415084 0.002301415
variance  0.043076439 0.0634798490 0.192712670

Estimators are close to their true values and the error metrics are low. We should be satisfied with these results.

The Cauchy distribution is known for its heavy tails, meaning it has a probability density function that can assign relatively high probabilities to extreme values, and it has no finite mean or variance. Because of its heavy tails and the absence of a finite mean, finding a suitable initial guess for the shift parameter (the location parameter) when fitting a Cauchy distribution to data can be challenging. But should we need to do so, the median would be a reasonable starting guess for the shift parameter. The median represents the point in the data where half of the observations fall below it, and half fall above it. This aligns well with the idea of estimating the "center" or "location" of a Cauchy distribution, which is what the shift parameter represents.

Excercise 7¶

In [ ]:
series = function(estimator, distribution, θ, sd, range = 20:100) {
	main.frame <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = 0, nrow = 4))
	for(n in range) {
		main.frame = data.frame(
			main.frame,
			estimate(
				estimator = estimator,
				distribution = distribution,
				θ = θ, sd = sd, n = n
			)
		)
	}
	colnames(main.frame) = range
	return(main.frame)
}

plot.series = function(a, b, c, metric = "MSE") {
	colors = c("#1b98e0", "#353436", "#923456")
	sample = as.numeric(colnames(a))
	plot(sample, c[metric,], ylab = metric, type="l", col=colors[1])
	lines(sample, b[metric,], col=colors[2])
	lines(sample, a[metric,], col=colors[3])
	legend(
		"topright",
		legend = c("c", "b", "a"),
		col = colors, lwd = 2,
		title = "Experiment"
	)
	title(metric, line = 1)
}

plot.series.full = function(a, b, c) {
	par(mfrow = c(1, 3))
	options(repr.plot.width=18, repr.plot.height=6)
	plot.series(a, b, c, metric = "MSE")
	plot.series(a, b, c, metric = "variance")
	plot.series(a, b, c, metric = "bias")
}

Cauchy distribution¶

In [ ]:

We can see that variance and also somewhat bias decrease universally with the sample size witch matches our intuition. We also discover that in the case of the poorly picked weighted sum estimator the MSE actually increases which is to be expected as it follows from its property we saw earlier to align well with the scale parameter. The shift and scale parameters there are respectively 1 and 2 and we have $MSE(1, 2) = 1$ which is the value we observe that particular estimator's MSE tending to.
